  <div class="box">
    <h3>AI Chat Interface</h3>
    <p>The chat interface was designed around a single constraint: every answer had to be verifiable without making verification feel like homework. In a tool where trust is the product, source attribution couldn't be a footnote — but it also couldn't fragment the reading experience into a wall of citations.</p>
    <p>The solution was a layered disclosure model: responses surface clean, plain-language answers first, with sources available inline but visually subordinate — accessible on demand rather than forced on every read. AI responses were streamed and rendered via <code>react-markdown</code> with <code>remark-gfm</code> and <code>rehype-raw</code>, giving the interface fine-grained control over how structured data, tables, and prose coexisted in a single response. <code>eventsource-parser</code> handled the streaming layer, keeping the interface alive and progressive during data retrieval. Loading states and latency were treated as interaction design problems — animation and progressive rendering maintained forward momentum during queries, keeping the interface feeling alive rather than stalled.</p>
  </div>

